<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <%- include("partials/headInfo") %>
  <body>
    <header>
      <h1> <a href="/">Data Structures</a> </h1>
      <h2> <%= title %> </h2>
    </header>
    <hr>
    <main>
        <%- include("partials/smallNav") %>
        <div>
            <img src=<%= image %> alt="Stack">
            <ul>
                <li> A stack is a data structure that is used to store data in a sequential order.</li>
                <li> The elements are stored in a last-in first-out order. (<strong>LIFO</strong>) </li>
                <li> A stack can be thought of like a stack of plates. It is easiest to interact with the plate on top. </li>
                <li>
                    <details>
                    <summary> A stack typically has three main functions: push, pop, and peek. </summary>
                    <ol>
                        <li> push adds an element to the top of the stack. </li>
                        <li> pop removes and returns the element at the top of the stack. </li>
                        <li> peek returns the element at the top of the stack without removing it. </li>
                    </ol>
                    </details>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <%- include("partials/visual") %>
        <div>
            <p class="example"> Push adds to the front of the stack, so push would add an element in front of <%= data[data.length-1] %>. </p>
            <p class="example"> Pop returns and removes the front of the stack, so it would take <%= data[data.length-1] %> off the stack and return it. </p>
            <p class="example"> Peek returns the front of the stack, so it would return <%= data[data.length-1] %>. </p>
        </div>
        <p> The back of the stack is not directly accessible. </p>
      <cite>Source: <a class="sourceLink" href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/stack-data-structure/">GeeksforGeeks</a> </cite>
    </main>
    <%- include("partials/footer") %>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>